---

# Repository Security & Governance

To maintain a secure, production-grade engineering environment, every developer, intern, QA engineer, and architect must follow these repository security practices.

## 1. Git Ignore

Never commit:

- `.env`
- `.env.local`
- Firebase credentials
- Google API credentials
- Google OAuth secrets
- Service account JSON files
- Resume PDFs
- Evidence documents
- Local databases
- Generated reports
- Temporary files

Only commit:

- `.env.example`

---

## 2. Pre-Commit Hooks (Mandatory)

Configure Git pre-commit hooks using Husky.

The pre-commit hook should automatically prevent commits if it detects:

- `.env` files
- Firebase credentials
- Google API secrets
- OAuth tokens
- Service account keys
- Private certificates
- PEM / P12 / PFX files
- Large generated files
- Accidentally committed evidence documents
- Build artifacts
- Node modules

The hook should also execute:

- ESLint
- TypeScript type checking
- Unit tests (where applicable)
- Secret detection

If any validation fails, the commit must be blocked.

---

## 3. GitHub Secret Scanning

Enable GitHub Secret Scanning for the repository.

Verify detection of:

- Firebase API keys
- Google OAuth credentials
- Service Account JSON keys
- GitHub Personal Access Tokens
- JWT secrets
- SSH private keys
- AWS / Azure / GCP credentials
- OpenAI API keys (future)
- Ollama configuration secrets (future)

Repository administrators should review and resolve all secret scanning alerts immediately.

---

## 4. Gitleaks

Integrate Gitleaks into the development workflow.

Run:

- Before every Pull Request
- During CI/CD pipeline
- Before production releases

The scan should detect:

- Hardcoded passwords
- API keys
- Private keys
- OAuth tokens
- Database connection strings
- Certificates
- Secrets accidentally added to source code

Pull Requests containing secrets must fail automatically.

---

## 5. Branch Protection

Protect the following branches:

- `main`
- `release/*`

Require:

- Pull Request
- Minimum one code review
- Passing CI checks
- No unresolved conversations
- No direct pushes

Only Platform Admins may merge into protected branches.

---

## 6. Code Review Requirements

Every Pull Request must include:

- Story ID
- Simulator ID (if applicable)
- Summary of changes
- Test evidence
- Security considerations
- Screenshots (if UI changed)
- Verification report link

No code should be merged without review.

---

## 7. Dependency Security

Before merging:

- Run `npm audit`
- Update vulnerable packages
- Remove unused dependencies
- Verify license compatibility
- Review newly added packages

High and Critical vulnerabilities must be resolved before release.

---

## 8. Security Validation

Every completed story should pass:

- ESLint
- TypeScript compilation
- Unit Tests
- Integration Tests
- Secret Scan
- Dependency Audit
- Manual Verification
- QA Review
- Architect Review

---

## 9. Developer Responsibilities

Every developer is responsible for:

- Never committing secrets
- Never committing production credentials
- Using feature branches
- Keeping commits small and meaningful
- Writing descriptive commit messages
- Updating documentation
- Uploading required engineering evidence
- Completing all Definition of Done items

---

## 10. Repository Health Checklist

Before every release verify:

- No secrets committed
- All CI checks passing
- Build successful
- Tests passing
- Security scan passed
- Dependency audit clean
- Documentation updated
- Story evidence complete
- QA approval received
- Architect approval received

---

## Future Enhancements

As the EV.ENGINEER platform evolves, implement the following repository governance improvements:

- Automated Dependency Updates (Dependabot or equivalent)
- Automated License Compliance Checks
- SBOM (Software Bill of Materials) generation
- CodeQL static analysis
- Signed commits for maintainers
- Signed release tags
- Automated release notes generation
- Conventional Commit enforcement
- Branch naming policy validation
- AI-assisted Pull Request review
- Automated architecture compliance checks
- Repository health dashboard
- Security scorecard reporting

These controls are not mandatory for the internship MVP but should be part of the long-term roadmap toward an aerospace-grade engineering platform.